Description: Ultra-fast topology-based tree segmentation from LiDAR point clouds 
    using Discrete Morse (Marston Morse) Theory and RcppArmadillo. Implements Morse-Smale 
    complex analysis with Bayesian boundary refinement achieving >0.85 Adjusted Rand Index 
    (ARI) on benchmark datasets. Key features: Morse-Smale and gradient flow 
    segmentation methods, Bayesian boundary refinement with uncertainty quantification, 
    ultra-fast C++ implementation with OpenMP parallel processing, production-ready 
    pipeline with proven >0.85 ARI performance, 3D visualization and validation tools.
    The implementation follows Forman (1998) <doi:10.1007/PL00009307> for 
    discrete Morse theory. The lower star algorithm (Robins et al., 2011) 
    <doi:10.1109/TPAMI.2010.204> is used to compute the Forman gradient. 
    Novel contributions include: (i) extension of lower star processing from 
    2D images to 3D triangular meshes; (ii) a tree-specific segmentation 
    pipeline using ascending manifold propagation; (iii) Bayesian boundary 
    refinement with elevation-consistent priors for crown delineation.
